reviews.name: Raymond H.
reviews.review: Whenever I visit San Francisco, I use this parking garage.  Mostly because of its location.  The garage is very clean and the security team is on duty paying close attention.  The early bird special fits my needs very well.

reviews.name: Sara R.
reviews.review: Myself and three others just left an event at the Masonic. The event staff inside the venue were fantastic, however the parking staff in the Masonic parking lot treated us terribly. Upon entry to our event (VIP dashboard confessional and third eye blind event) there was a sign posted saying event parking was $30.  We also received an email from live nation stating the parking was $30. When we paid we were charged $38. The parking attendant called the lot manager, who was EXTREMELY rude to us. He was rude, and talked down to us like a bully and said there was no sign because the event didn't start until 4, when in fact the VIP event started much earlier. He told us too bad, and that he's the manager and no one is going to give us our money back. We asked him if he put up the sign himself and he said no. He said "well did you take a picture of the sign? Do you have proof?" He was really mean to us, all over a measly $8. We are more upset over how degrading his speech was than the money itself. We are surely never parking in this parking garage again. He also refused to give our parking ticket back, and when we tried to leave he wouldn't let us out and made us back up and go around just to be rude. We felt like he basically told us to f-off. (Sorry about the language)

reviews.name: Jennie P.
reviews.review: I went monthly at state garage in january 2015 up to May 3 2015. I had no problems all attendants were professionals treated me kindly and were highly informative of monthly rate  how to pay and what was expected. My number was 576 and I truly respect these men who job is customer service with positive attitude and kindness since all they do is park cars and retrieve autos to person daily. I had no problem  all workers from time of open to close were just remarkably respectful professionals with sense of humor. They have rules posted  as you enter the garage. I will always park my car at the state garage whenever I'm in the nob hill neighborhood.

reviews.name: Andrew G.
reviews.review: I asked the attendant the charge for parking overnight, to which he answered $30.00.  I told him I would need three days, so he told me it would be $90.00 (made sense).  When I came back the next day and told him I only needed two days, he quickly told me that two days was $45.00 per day (the same as three).  I asked him to show me where that was posted and he could not.  He became very upset and told me to be quiet and listen to him.  I told him that I thought he was very dishonest (and a few other things) and left.  I am currently disputing this with my credit card company.

reviews.name: L D.
reviews.review:
There was a misunderstanding about me taking my car vs. needing to grab something.  When the manager found out I was simply grabbing something, he lost it on me, started yelling, told me to get out, told me my month contract was cancelled (I was only three days in), and told me to leave.  He tried to reach into my car to grab the monthly parking permit from my rear window, which I obviously need to get a refund.

A few notes- The garage was very busy and I waited for 15 minutes while they attended to other customers and grabbed my car.  I understand they were really busy, so told them not to worry, that I would park my car on the street and then return later in the evening.  This didn't keep the manager from yelling at me.  He escalated the situation, told me my contract was "cancelled".

I returned to ask for a refund for the days I wont be using.  The manager claimed he can't process the refund, that it needs to come from the management office, and that I would only get 50% back.

reviews.name: Amy H.
reviews.review: Would give zero stars if I could. Tried parking here last night for a show at Regency Ballroom. Circled around a couple times, didn't see street parking so pulled in here for $15 parking. Improvised written sign (paper on wall) said close at midnight. Actual sign at entrance says close at 2am on weekends! Guy comes up, immediately starts jabbering away about I have to be back by 11:45 or he locks the gate and it's $30 to get my car in morning. I'm all smiles and laughing and in good spirit despite, say I am going to show will be back, no problem, etc. In the meantime he's asking me why I don't park in the street, says there's parking there, etc etc. I'm like, I'm in a rush already and feel safer leaving my car in garage. He takes my $20, continues blabbering, saying I could park in the street. I'm just laughing nicely still, again point out I'm in a rush would prefer to park and go. Ask about the hours posted. He's like, 11:45 is when YOU must be here, midnight is when I GO HOME. I'm just like okay, no problem, maybe should change the signs to reflect actual business hours, all very nicely. At that point he tells me to leave, to go park on the street. Rudely and curtly. I'm like, still super friendly, but I ask him, what? Are you serious? You don't want my money? You don't want my business? Really? He responds no, continues being a jerk, hands me my $20 back and watched as I had to back up down the long narrow entrance and leave. I couldn't find street parking, ended up at an
Sunday morning and waiting for the lot to open. WTF

reviews.name: Marlene P.
reviews.review: I parked in this garage from 4:24 to 6:40 p.m. yesterday.  It features an automated parking system called Autopark and is under the auspices of Ace Parking of San Francisco.  I paid in case at the machine in the lobby of the building and was charged the exorbitant sum of $27.  That's bad enough.  I paid with two $20 bills.  After I'd inserted the first $20, the machine prompted me to insert more money.  After inserting the second $20, I was informed that the machine owed me $13.  It returned only $8.  While I was reacting to that, the robovoice inside the thieving device asked if I wanted a receipt.  Before I could press the button, the machine cut off access to it and returned to its resting state, leaving me without either the $5 it had stolen from me or the receipt.  I want my $5 back and I should like to know that someone is investigating this machine to determine what is wrong with its settings.  It may well be doing this to a large number of people every day, exacting its own robo-tolls.  I know it's only $5, but I am not willing to let this go and will press Ace Parking to correct this situation.
